## Post 1

Post Link: https://www.linkedin.com/posts/katebour_not-all-proof-is-created-equal-heres-how-activity-7449792938512891905-pOd2?utm_source=share&utm_medium=member_desktop&rcm=ACoAAE1kWlsB3eTG7rR6KYq4IK5u4NC0ZAoRoWs  
Date: April 15, 2026

Not all proof is created equal.
Here’s how to rank yours:
So if you’ve been following me for a while or done any of my programs, then you already know that I talk about proof… A LOT.
You can have the best product in the world, but without proof? Every sale will be a slog.
There are 8 different types of proof, and I’ve experienced them all—from being featured in Inc Magazine and winning international design awards to getting unsolicited shoutouts from smart, respected people.
(One tweet from Amanda Natividad once sent me 3,500 new Twitter followers overnight.)

If you’re trying to use proof more strategically, think of it in tiers:
→ Tier 1: Borrowed proof  
→ Tier 2: Self-reported results  
→ Tier 3: Paid media mentions  
→ Tier 4: Solicited testimonials  
→ Tier 5: Earned third-party recognition  
→ Tier 6: Unsolicited customer praise  
→ Tier 7: Demonstrated results  
→ Tier 8: Endorsement from a highly trusted source  

What kind of proof are you using in your business?
Most experts mostly stick to Tiers 1 and 2. The higher tiers are where clients actually convert.
Makes sense, right?

### Insight:
- Introduces a clear hierarchy of proof (highly actionable framework)
- Connects credibility directly to conversion (key B2B principle)
- Uses tiered structure to simplify complex concept
- Reinforces importance of third-party validation over self-promotion

## Post 2
Post Link:https://www.linkedin.com/posts/katebour_your-buyers-brain-is-lazy-thats-why-your-activity-7449430967091499008-2sz_?utm_source=share&utm_medium=member_desktop&rcm=ACoAAE1kWlsB3eTG7rR6KYq4IK5u4NC0ZAoRoWs
Date: April 14,2026

Your buyer’s brain is lazy. That’s why your positioning can’t be.
Have you lost work to someone you’re objectively better than?
It stings.
Maybe you found out later. Maybe you just suspected. The thinking was shallower, the track record thinner. But they got the call because they were top-of-mind.
It’s not fair. But it’s how buying decisions actually get made.
When someone needs to hire an expert, there’s rarely a painstaking process where they evaluate all possible options against carefully curated criteria.
It works more like… autocomplete.
The person who owns a specific space in the buyer’s brain gets in the consideration set.
Type “marketer.” Crowded results page, no clear winner. The brain sputters and stalls.
Type “ownable ideas.” One mental result.
The science behind top-of-mind positioning:
→ System 1 thinking: Most decisions are automatic and unconscious  
→ Neural networks: Specific ideas create stronger mental associations  
→ Availability heuristic: Easy recall is perceived as quality  

Your buyer’s lazy brain makes the shortlist. It’s your job to position yourself so clearly—and to repeat the same sharp idea so compellingly—that your name gets autofilled when people need your thing.
That’s how you win.
--
PS: I write about the psychology behind ownable ideas every week in my Unignorable newsletter.

### Insight:
- Explains positioning using behavioral psychology (System 1 thinking, heuristics)
- Strong metaphor (“autocomplete”) simplifies complex decision-making process
- Emphasizes importance of clarity and repetition in brand positioning
- Connects mental availability directly to winning business opportunities
